text: All these people complaining in the comments that there's no Venom in the trailer. It's the first teaser trailer, why show your hand this early? They've got plenty of time to build hype before the big reveal. We can assume from the jar of black goop and the poster art we'll have all the classic Venom features, the jet-black fluid skin, the white eyes and wide smile. We all already know what Venom looks like, so this first trailer teases some themes, characters and story element. Patience is a virtue and pays dividends. Don't hate on something just because it's still trying to build hype rather than serve as simple wish fulfillment.

text: This is like a Spiderman trailer, but if they only showed Peter Parker doing typical generic high school drama stuff. This is a trailer for a movie called Venom, but all we see is a bunch of typical tropes every other low budget movie has. The trailer even points them out. text: Venom without Spider-Man isn't Venom. He's a character defined entirely - in look, personality, origin, motive, and abilities - by his relationship to Spidey. His name literally implies that he's Spider-Man's venom...   To get Tom Fucking Hardy for what looks like an extremely loose adaptation of such an iconic character is a giant slap in the face to the fans.   What makes it more ridiculous is the fact that Sony is partnering with Marvel on Spidey in the MCU, meaning they could've made this a proper adaptation. Even if Tom Holland cameos, it won't mean anything unless he and Eddie are at odds with each other.

text: Okay so a couple of things here.   1. I like the idea of the vigilante aspect. In the comics, Eddie did indeed move to San Fransico and Venom was a vigilante there for a bit before Carnage's appearance forced him back to New York. 2. I'm confused with the symbiote's role in this. Is it the outer-space goo from the Amazing universe, or is it the supposed "Cure for cancer" that Eddie Brock Sr. and Richard Parker cooked up in the ultimate universe. 3. IF Holland is indeed tied to this film (says "rumored" on IMDB) then this is another MCU-linked movie, which I like. 4. You don't show Venom at all. I  can understand "making us wait" but COME ON! Even Spider-Man 3's trailer had Venom in it!

text: I wanted to be hyped for this, but it's just not happening. I liked parts of it, but I just can't get that little voice in the back of my head that keeps saying this is going to be a colossal failure to shut up. It's not because they didn't show Venom either. I know what Venom looks like, and can pretty much guess what he'll look like in this, so I don't need to see it. There was just something about it that said they're trying too hard, and it's not working. I want it to be good, because I love Venom, and I want to see the character finally done justice on the big screen. This will almost certainly be better than Spider-Man 3, but will it be good? I don't know.

text: I haven't seen enough to judge this movie yet...  But neither have you numbskulls. Stop crapping on this trailer just because it didn't show Venom in action. It's called a *"teaser"* for a reason. Venom is a character with a look people have been wanting to be properly brought to life for *years.* This is a different thing than the Deadpool costume or the Spiderman costume. You can't just throw it on screen; This something to build up anticipation for!   That said, I would be lying if I didn't wish there was at least a clip of his silhouette stalking in the shadows or something.   But like I said, it's not fair to judge yet people. So quite jumping to conclusions.  Besides, as bad as this may possibly turn out, there's no way it could be worse than Spiderman 3's sorry excuse for an adaptation.  ... Right?

text: Well when I opened the trailer I immediately saw the amount of dislikes and got worried that the movie is going to be horrible. But that's not what happened, people are just upset because nothing actually happens, just a couple of scenes with barely anything of Venom in it, and more importantly no shots of the Venom itself.  Now I'm just relieved because that doesn't mean the movie itself is going to be bad, it's just that they decided to not show anything relevant in the teaser trailer at all, surely that will disappoint people who expected to see how Venom will look like, but that also means they could be saving the best for last.  I didn't really like this teaser trailer aswell, but I'm at least glad that it doesn't really show anything bad at all, it's not like the X-men Apocalipse where the instant we saw how Apocalipse looked like, we all knew that was not going to be it .

While I hate the lack of the gamma bomb in the film and tv versions of the Hulk, the Hulk's personality and motivations aren't really influenced by the gamma bomb, but by Banner's inner demons. With Venom, however, Spider-Man is THE major influence in it's origin and a motivation for Eddie Brock. That is, unless what I read in the 90s has been retconned.   I'm a huge fan of Tom Hardy, but unless the origin follows the comic, it won't seem like the real Venom to me.  Does anyone know if it's following the comic origin?

text: For a trailer in February for a movie that comes out in October, this was a good TEASER trailer. I like the tone, I like the talent they have, I honestly really liked this trailer.  I‚Äôm kind of surprised that there‚Äôs so many people disappointed with it in regards to them not showing Venom. I mean, let‚Äôs be real here, at this stage you don‚Äôt want them to show him, because by all means he‚Äôll look pretty bad.  Besides, I guarantee you that in the trailers to come, you‚Äôll see plenty of Venom shots. My fear is that Sony will do what they‚Äôve continued to do with all of their big trailers, including Spider-Man: Homecoming, which is give away the entire movie in the trailer. That‚Äôs probably another factor why I like this one so much, because it just gives us a glimpse into the movie.  I really enjoyed it, surprised more people didn‚Äôt, but I‚Äôm very excited to see my favorite super villain on the big screen.

Not because they didn't show Venom [I think that's cool, actually] but because the narrator's voice was weak and because the scenes they chose to show felt random and nonsensical. It would've been better if they just showed the close-up of Tom Hardy on the hospital bed, slowly going crazy, while a narrator with a more chilling voice did the narration. Maybe even hard cut to Tom running through the woods at the end of the trailer.  But, still, it's Venom and Tom Hardy, so I'll definitely be seeing this one.

text: Without Spider-Man I don't understand how this movie is going to work. Yeah Venom is an anti-hero (sort of) but you need a protagonist - every story follows a character you get behind in some way. If Eddie Brock is troubled sure...but Venom is murderous and cold-blooded. They're going to have to sacrifice something here with the character to make it work like that. And if he battles Carnage you either root for a killer or a more evil killer? Who is the protagonist/antagonist here? It doesn't make much sense. Venom is at his strongest when he has Spider-Man to bounce off of - they're yin and yang. If Sony thinks Venom is just all muscles and violence then they don't understand the character at all.

But first of all, there has been good Venom stories in the comics where spidey doesn't appear and second, has it been confirmed that this is an origin story? text: The film adaptation will be based on the story Venom: Lethal Protector (in this story venom left new York city in San Francisco). Eddie Brock in this comic was a hero and tried to stop the other symbiotes that were born because of him.  Trailer teaser that Eddie Brock was a volunteer in the Life Foundation program, but apparently not for all volunteers participating in the program ended successfully.  Life Foundation pharmaceutical organization will play a key role in the film, as based on venom they will create other symbiotes (five: Agony, Phage, Scream, Riot and Lasher), which will later get out of control.  It is not known which version of the origin of venom will be presented in the film, classic or Ultimate (in this version of venom is the result of attempts to create a cure for cancer).  But, most likely, the classic story will be adapted (though with a number of changes), because in the trailer there are scenes with the collapse of an unknown object. Perhaps a spacecraft, where the symbiote came to Earth.

text: "Your" is used when you refer to someone's possession. For example, 'He looks like YOUR dad' or, 'is that YOUR bag?'.  "You're", on the other hand is actually the short form for "You are". Examples I'll give are, 'YOU'RE a very smart person' and 'YOU'RE the reason I'm writing this'.   Please spread this around for the benefit of people who are oblivious to this simple distinction: YOUR refers to someone's possession and YOU'RE is actually the same as YOU ARE. Thank you.

Last time I checked Venom is as about as far from a protector as you can get, but I'm open to new interpretations of the character. I'm curious how they will do a Venom movie without Spiderman (if hes not in this movie) considering that the whole reason Venom looks the way he does and has similar powers to Spiderman is because the symbiote first infected Spiderman and became obsessed with him. It then infected Eddie Brock because he hated Spiderman at the time for a lot of misfortune that befell him in his life. Spiderman is the whole reason Venom exists as he does. I hope it's a good film but I'm a little worried as this comes across like Sony wanting to have it's cake and eat it too.

text: This should be interesting. It's basically impossible to do a 1:1 copy of the comic book origin for Venom, so "odd alien lifeform with unclear origin" is probably the best we'll get for the symbiote. That said, one key component is that said symbiote was bonded to peter parker before he rejected it and it found Eddie Brock. That said, they can slightly gloss over it and mention it in passing and have a movie about Venom knowing who they are and their sense of vigilante justice. Especially since they are experimenting on both the symbiote and Eddie, we have a whole organization for them to go bananas against.

text: Everyone needs to chill about where's venom? There's a reason this trailer isn't titled, "Venom Movie Trailer," instead of TEASER Trailer. The reason why they don't show venom, is to leave you wanting more and wanting to watch the next trailer and the movie when it comes out. This is why I like this trailer it relates perfectly to the comic it's based on. It starts first to focus on Eddie Brock and how he acquired the symbiote from The Life Foundation and morphed with it to become Venom. At 1:16, the symbiote- which is already inside Eddie brock- is reacting to the MRI scan because Brock has cancer, and the machine looking for it is extremely loud, which cause the symbiote to rage inside of Brock which is why we very shortly see black veins going up his neck. This will most likely be when he transforms into Venom in the movie so keep an eye out for this seen and just wait patiently for the next trailer and hope Venom is in it.

text: Venom makes an agreement with Spider-Man that they will leave each other alone, on the condition that Venom commits no crimes. Venom then moves from New York City to San Francisco, and takes up with a group of Californian mole people. Shortly thereafter the father of one of Venom's victims seeks him out with a group of super-powered mercenaries to take revenge. Spider-Man, seeing misleading coverage of Venom on television, heads to San Francisco to confront him and instead winds up fighting alongside Venom against five new offspring of the Venom Symbiote: Scream, Phage, Riot, Lasher, and Agony. this is how the comic goes and in the description, they clam venom as the "lethal Protector" so I'm not sure if this is how the movie will play out (the comic is Venom: Lethal Protector")

text: Hardy is an excellent choice physically and as an actor for the character especially when compared to the only other person to play the part, Topher Grace. Sorry but Grace was a real bad miscast imo, particularly when it comes to his size. Brock in the comics was a big dude, nowhere near what could be defined as skinny.  I thought Grace did an OK job, however, Rami's Spider-Man 3 movie was bloated with villains to begin with, not giving an iconic villain like Venom the justice onscreen that it deserved. We can hope that this movie does a much better job with the character, and I'm hoping it leads to a Spider-Man - Venom movie, which if done well could be incredible.

text: the venom symbiote releases a telepathic scream into space that crash lands an alien ship here on earth for help. the life corporation finds the ship and starts making symbiote clones from the original symbiote (venom). these clones are Agony, Lasher, Riot, Rage, and Scream. eddie brock as Venom must now destroy these creations that were spawned from him while juggling his marriage with his wife(later becomes she-venom). eddie tries to contemplate his relationship with the venom suit and leaves the symbiote on it's own while thinking. the clones start using parts of the suits to take over civilian minds while also gathering machine parts to make a teleporter to get back home. at some point while fighting the clones, eddie falls into the teleporter and sees a world conquered by symbiotes, and venom reveals it's nature to him. venom was an outcast for wanting to bond with it's host rather than dominate it, and joins back with eddie. they go back through the teleporter to earth and destroy the clones. by the end of the film(or in the sequel) carnage will appear, having absorbed all the symbiotes from the other world and grown to the size of a building and will fight venom and spiderman(maybe a cameo?).........and that's pretty much venom.

Sorry Silent Bob,  I love you,  but the concern that the movie has no connection to the Secret Wars, and why is the symbiote in the jar. For any Venom fan,  especially those who have read the Ultimate version of Spider-Man, know that there is certainly more than than one possible explanation to the existence of the symbiote. text: Dear Sony,   Stop trying to establish your bullshit Spider-Man character universe. You have made two insufferable and cringe-worthy garbage movies trying to establish  the universe of the so-called "Amazing Spider-Man", that caused you guys to give Spider-Man back to the smarter writers and directors of Marvel Studios , which enabled them to make a FAR SUPERIOR Spider-Man character in less than eight minutes of screen time in Captain America Civil War. You guys made the deal with them, and profited from Homecoming's box office sales. And yet still, you guys are trying to establish your own Spider-Man related films that are not connected to the MCU, and will undoubtedly ruin Venom, one of Spidey's most popular and iconic villains, for the SECOND F*CKING TIME. Just stop with this nonsense already!!!. When are you guys going to get this through your head?! The same thing goes with that Spider-Man: Into the Spider-Verse movie which will most likely also bomb. ENOUGH is ENOUGH. Please scrap these phony ideas of yours and let Marvel handle the creative work from now on please! It's what we all want and deserve.

text: I feel Eddie Brock should always be "Venom". In fact, I'm not a fan of most tangents that Marvel has been doing with changing identity and ultimately brand of most famous characters/heroes in the comics. Marvel needs to be more original and come up with fresh new characters instead of rewriting existing brands/characters to push their political agenda. I'm not the only one that feels this way, It's reflected in sales that the core audience does not like this either. If you want diversity, then give the creative team a chance to come up with new interesting characters. Spawn is one of my favorite characters of all time, who just so happens to be African American. Marvel needs to take their time and come up with something original instead of rewriting characters/brands that have been around for 50 years...

text: there is a very simple way to make a Venom movie: 1: Give SOME backstory for Eddie Brock. Not too much, but just enough. 2: Have him be a complete asshole for like the the first 3rd of the movie until he gets the symbiote. He then learns how to control the symbiote after a few outbursts. 3: Have Eddie be accused of a murder. This way he gets imprisoned in the same room as our villain, Cletus Kassidy, Carnage. The symbiote gets him out of the cell, but a drop is saved by Cletus because he is a cannibal. Kassidy tries to escape, but is hit by a guard giving him a nosebleed. Blood drops onto the symbiote and Cletus eats it. 4: If Carnage is the villain, have a scene where Cletus is about to be killed by the electric chair, but the symbiote activates. He goes on a massacre. 5: Have Eddie feel guilt for creating Carnage and try to stop him. He first encounters him when Carnage tries to kill Brock. Venom goes to the prison Carnage was placed in and finds out where Kassidy had a hideout. Venom goes there and finds a list of his future victims, people who stalked until he could kidnap them and take them to his hideout.Carnage attacks and chases Venom through a sewer. 6: The final battle should be in a lab where Carnages last victim is. Venom tries to hold off Carnage while the scientists active a total lockdown. The power goes off and now it is a predator v. prey fight. Cannage stalks the lad for Eddie, accidentally lighting a propane tank showing the sybiotes weakness. Venom defeats Carnage using the propane, injuring himself in the process.  Cletus kills  himself while Venom tries to claw his way out. Venom gets out, but is faced with a SWAT team. At first his animal instincts make him grow big and threaten the SWAT, but he sees the scientists that he saved, calms down, and says, "The real monster is inside, dead. Don't follow me." He jumps away and out of sight. From this moment on, he is Venom, lethal protector.

text: Now, many people do need to realize that the reason why this trailer didn't receive good reviews is because of the 'high-demand' from viewers about seeing the character of Venom when there were those at the studio trying to continue their work on the visual effects. It's almost like when people complained about 2012's Prometheus movie because it didn't mention the 'xenomorphs', so Ridley Scott was pressured to introduce the 'xenomorphs' too soon in his next movie Alien: Covenant and people were somewhat disappointed with the outcome. Thus, leaving the future of the Alien movies in question. I say that people need to have some faith as well as patience when it comes to these things. But in any case, I do hope that this Venom movie does well.
